Torsit seems to indicate a wavering, unsteady line. The phrase occurs in Stat. Theb. 11. 312-3 paulum si devius hostis Torsit iter. but in a different sense, meaning merely “turned aside.''

iter: accusative of inner object. male: owing to the trembling of her fingers.

aper: the Thesaurus gives no instance of the use of apex to mean pen. The word, however, indicates any pointed top or end, e. g. of a spear, cf. Sil. 1. 466—7 iacit tyneus hastae Dirum lumen apex.

Hence it might easily be applied to the stilus. A pezc was also the name given to the sign placed over a long vowel to indicate its quantity, and from this in late Latin it came to mean a letter, then writing or any- thing written. The latter is probably the meaning in Anth. 107. 5 apicum dat selle fiyuras, though possibly it may there mean pen.

notat: Ovid frequently uses noto to mean write ; cf. Met. 9. 522-3 Incipit, et dubitat· scribit, damnatque tabellas,· Et notat et delen· mutat, culpatque, probatque.
